        <div id="page-container">
        
			<h2>BASICS</h2>
			<h3><u>Tokens</u></h3>

                        <p> Tokens are the smallest individual unit of a program</p>
			<p> Keywords, Identifiers, Constants, Strings, Special Symbols, and Operators are the tokens in C++</p>


                    <br>
		    <h3><u>Keywords</u></h3>
		    
			<p> Keywords are reserved words that have a special meaning associated with them</p>
			<p>For example:
			<ul>
			   <li>int</li>
			   <li>float</li>
			   <li>short</li>
			   <li>Protected</li>
			   <li>union</li>
			   <li>TRUE/FALSE</li>
			</ul>
			and so on</p>
			<br>
		<h3><u>Identifiers</h3></u>
		<p>An identifier is nothing but a name assigned to an element in a program.</p>
		<h4><u>Rules for naming identifiers</h4></u>
		<ul>
			<li>The first character of an identifier can only begin with a character or an underscore</li>
			<li>An identifier cannot begin with a special character</li>
			<li>A keyword cannot be an identifier</li>
			<li>Leaving white spaces is discouraged - instead separate the words using an underscore</li>
			<li>C++ is case sensitive - upper and lowecase letters are considered to be different</li>
		</ul>		
<br>
		<h3><u>Constants</h3></u>
		<p>Constants are fixed values that cannot change their value during the entire program as soon as we define them</p>
		<h4><u>Types of constants in C++</h4></u>
		<ul>
			<li>Integer constants - 5, 6, 100, 60</li>
			<li>Floating constants - 7.9, 7.0444, 4.09</li>
			<li>Character constants - const char answer = 'y'</li>
			<li>String constants - const char title[] = "HelloWorld"</li>
		</ul>
	<br>
		<h3><u>Operators in C++</u></h3>
		<p>Operators are tools or symbols which are used to perform a specific operation on data. Operations are performed on operands.</p>
		<h4><u>Types of operators</h4></u>
		<ol>
			<li>Unary Operators -  It involves the use of one a single operand. e.g. '!' is a unary operator.</li><br>
			<li>Binary Operators - It involves the use of two operands.</li>
			<h4><u>Types of binary operators</h4></u>
			<ul>
				<li>Arithmetic</li>
				<ol>
					<li>Addition +</li>
					<li>Subtraction -</li>
					<li>Multiplication *</li>
					<li>Division /</li>
					<li>Modulus %</li>
					<li>Increment ++</li>
					<li>Decrement --</li>
				</ol>
				<li>Relational - e.g. ==, !=, >, <, >=, <=</li>
				<li>Logical - e.g. &&, ||, !</li>
				<li>Assignment - e.g. =, +=, -=, *=, /=, %=, &=, |=, ^=, >>=, <<=</li>
				<li>Bitwise</li>
				<li>Conditional</li>
			</ul><br>
			<li>Ternary Operators - It involves the use of three operands</li>
			</ol>
<br>

